Trump and the Economy
New York—Financial markets finally woke up to the fact that Trump is the President of the United States.
The world has endured the unfiltered tweets and public remarks of the world's most powerful person for two years, and the obvious question is: what has kept this going for so long?
On the other hand, investors have, until now, artificially kept Trump's promises at arm's length.
As long as he implements tax cuts, deregulation, and other policies beneficial to the business sector and shareholders, they are willing to give him the benefit of the doubt.
Many believe that in the end, "the grown-ups in the room" will constrain Trump to ensure that government policy stays on track.
This assumption was largely confirmed during Trump's first year in office, a period when economic growth and expectations of increased corporate profits — thanks to impending tax cuts and deregulation — propelled strong stock market performance.
In 2017, the US stock index rose by more than 20%.
But in 2018, things took a turn for the worse, especially in the last few months.
Despite a more than 20% increase in corporate profits (thanks to tax cuts), the US stock market fluctuated for much of the year and is now experiencing a sharp decline.
Currently, various indices are in correction territory (down 10% from recent highs), with tech stock indices (such as the Nasdaq) having fallen into a bear market (down 20% or more).
Despite the increased volatility in financial markets reflecting concerns about China, Italy, and other eurozone economies, as well as key emerging markets, the recent turmoil is attributable to Trump.
At the beginning of this year, Trump implemented reckless tax cuts, which pushed up long-term interest rates and brought the economy, already接近充分就业, to a peak.
By February, concerns over inflation rising above the Federal Reserve's target of 2% triggered the first risk-off episode of 2018.
Then, Trump launched a trade war against China and other important U.S. trading partners.
Market concerns over government protectionist policies have fluctuated throughout the year but are now reaching new heights.
The recent actions by the U.S. against China seem aimed at initiating a comprehensive trade, economic, and geo-political cold war.
Another concern is that other Trump policies could lead to stagflation (weak growth and rising inflation).
After all, Trump was preparing to restrict foreign direct investment inflows and implemented broad immigration restrictions, which will拖累 labor supply growth in a context where the aging workforce and skill mismatches are becoming increasingly severe.
Additionally, the Trump administration has yet to propose an infrastructure plan to stimulate private-sector productivity or accelerate the transition to a green economy.
In tweets and other forums, Trump continuously criticized corporate hiring, production, investment, and pricing behaviors, especially those of tech companies, which already faced widespread opposition and increasing competition from Chinese rivals.
Emerging markets have also been impacted by US policies.
Fiscal stimulus and monetary policy tightening pushed up both short-term and long-term interest rates, strengthening the dollar.
As a result, emerging economies faced capital outflows and an increase in the value of dollar-denominated debt.
Emerging economies heavily reliant on exports have suffered losses due to falling commodity prices, and even countries with indirect trade ties to China have felt the impact of the trade war.
Even Trump's oil policies have contributed to market volatility.
The reimposition of US sanctions on Iran drove up oil prices, but subsequent US government threats to revoke exemptions and pressure Saudi Arabia to increase oil production led to a dramatic drop in oil prices.
Despite lower oil prices benefiting American consumers, energy company stocks have struggled.
Moreover, excessive price volatility in oil is detrimental to both producers and consumers, as it hinders wise investment and consumption decisions.
Worse still, now it is clear that almost all the benefits of last year’s tax cuts have flowed to the corporate sector rather than to households in the form of higher real (inflation-adjusted) wages.
This means household consumption may soon decelerate further, thereby impacting the economy.
However, the primary reason for the recent dramatic plunge in US and global stock markets is Trump's own words and actions.
Worse still, the突出风险 of a full-scale trade war with China (despite his recent truce with Chinese President Xi Jinping) was compounded by Trump's public criticism of the Federal Reserve. His attacks began in the spring of 2018 when US GDP growth exceeded 4%.
